where host is the address of the nick, and server is the irc-server it resides on. ( %host is optional) As usually used: "/msg w@channels.undernet.org command-containing-password", assures that noone can fetch your password by using channel service. On Undernet, it couldn’t happen anyway, because theese nicks are blocked for normal users, but many people make mirc send their password to the bots automatically when they log onto IRC, and could then reavel their password if they logged onto other nets containing false w/x.<BR>
If you want your script to send someone some secret information, this might sound like an easy way to authenticate him, but there’s two problems: Someone could fake the host-address, or incidentally have the same one, and people change irc-server all the time, but the "@server" part isn’t optional, and can’t even have wildcards. This leaves you with a lot of extra scripting to fetch his server, and no real security. <BR>
Other approaches involves making your own password-system or verifying him through x/w if he logs onto them. Still then, the traffic on irc goes unencrypted around the world, so don’t reveal your credit-card-number here, ok? :-)<BR>
Example: <BR>
The nick Timo has the address "*.surfers.org" and is using the irc-server "Oslo-R.NO.EU.Undernet.org"<BR>
"/msg Timo%*.surfers.org@Oslo-R.NO.EU.Undernet.org Hi there! You won’t see this if you don’t match my criteria" <BR>
